SIMPLE: misericordia
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Misericordia
<hw>Mis`e*ri*cor"di*a</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.,
mercy, compassion; <ets>miser</ets> wretched + <ets>cor</ets>,
<ets>cordis</ets>, heart.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(O. Law)</fld> <def>An amercement.</def>
<rj><au>Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Anc. Armor.)</fld> <def>A thin-bladed dagger; so
called, in the Middle Ages, because used to give the death wound or
⟦ldquo⟧mercy⟦rdquo⟧ stroke to a fallen adversary.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>An indulgence as to food or dress
granted to a member of a religious order.</def>
<rj><au>Shipley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 930 --></p>

<p><ent>Miserly</ent>⟦br⟧
